metadata.name: Hexagones Landscape #299
metadata.description:
An undulating (sometimes) landscape made up of hexagons (or "Hexagones" laying in wait) to celebrate the first birthday of fxhash. Written at the last minute the weekend before the birthday week.

A simpler 16 colour version of this project was originally coded on an Atari ST 512, about 32 years ago, figured it was time to update it.

INSTRUCTIONS ::

h - Toggle high-res
s - Download and save image

PRINTING INSTRUCTIONS ::

High-res will output a 6,553 x 8,192 image, at 300dpi it should print at...

21.84 x 27.3 inches
55.47 x 69.3 cm

metadata.name: Gammalt #87
metadata.description:
Celebrating getting old with Fx(hash).

Save as png:
Click ‚Äús‚Äù
or double click/tap

Resolution:
Default image width = 2000px and aspect ratio = 4:3.
Modify the image width between 2000px and 10000px by adding ‚Äú&w=xxxx‚Äù to the url (e.g. &w=4000).
High resolutions are computationally expensive and may take a while.

Background:
The canvas background texture is visible by default. This can be toggled off by adding ‚Äú&b=0‚Äù to the url.
The background scales with resolution to mimic a bigger canvas so it will look different at different resolutions.
At high resolutions a Moir√© pattern may appear on the canvas background texture due to the way images are resized in the browser. It‚Äôs always recommended to download a full resolution version of the piece.

By KRANKARTA
Created on Firefox desktop 105.0 on 2022-11-11 in javascript and GLSL.
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Annum #8122
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

50% of primary sales go to Savepakistan.

metadata.name: Modulation #136
metadata.description:
Isometric cityscapes, patterns and geometries generated by trigonometric functions and rendered as SVG.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000√ó7500.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: vapour trails #32
metadata.description:
‚Äúfirst you look so strong, then you fade away
the sun will blind my eyes, i‚Äôll love you anyway
thirsty for your smile, i watch you for a while
you are a vapour trail in a deep blue sky‚Äù

‚Äî Andy Bell (Ride) (1991)

this collection tries to capture that feeling of lying in the grass
in a park
staring at the sky
fantasizing about your love (if they even exist)
playing out different paths
while smoke from your cigarette (jazz or otherwise)
trails between you and the faraway of everything
feeling grateful to not have to be anywhere
but here (now)

with luck
they lay next to you
and silently you appreciate each tick of the clock
wasted together
until life again gets in the way
and pulls you back
into the fray

[ live view commands ]
[ M : toggle matte ]
[ S : save current size ]
[ 1 : save 2000x3000 png ]
[ 2 : save 4000x6000 png ]
[ 3 : save 6000x9000* png ]
[ 4 : save 8000x12000* png ]
[ 5 : save 10000x15000* png ]

* higher resolutions can take a while to render.

twitter: @heyjeres

xoxo

metadata.name: fx(mash) #219
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: Miniscapes #203
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)
